{{Quote|She is a ''strange'' one&mdash;even among the Jedi. Her devotion to the Force is such that she even renounced her own name as a sign of selfless fealty. She is known only as&hellip;the ''Dark Woman!''|Lekket|<ref name="Star Wars (1998) 29">[[Star Wars (1998) 29|''Star Wars'' (1998) 29]]</ref>}}
'''An'ya Kuro''' was a [[Human/Legends|Human]] [[Gender/Legends|female]] who gave up her name in service of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] and became '''The Dark Woman'''. A mysterious yet respected [[Jedi Master/Legends|Master]] of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]] during the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], the Dark Woman [[Jedi training/Legends|trained]] several [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitives]] of later prominence in the [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] arts. However, it was her failure to successfully train a female student named [[Aurra Sing/Legends|Aurra Sing]]&mdash;who later earned a reputation as a notorious [[Jedi hunter/Legends|slayer of Jedi]]&mdash;that caused the Dark Woman to enter a self-imposed exile on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Cophrigin V]].

The Dark Woman later returned to the Jedi Order in accordance with the will of the Force to participate in the Clone Wars as a [[Spy/Legends|spy]]. During the onset of the [[Great Jedi Purge/Legends|Great Jedi Purge]], Kuro went into hiding until she was discovered and struck down by [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]].

==Biography==
===Early life===
{{Quote|A Jedi should have no possessions. Not even an identity. I gave mine up to show humility before the Force.''"<br />"''Instead you allowed them to call you 'The Dark Woman.' Such an improvement!|An'ya Kuro and Tholme|<ref name="Jedi: Aayla Secura">''[[Jedi: Aayla Secura]]''</ref>}}
[[File:Intangibility.jpg|thumb|left|250px|An'ya Kuro leaves the presence of the Jedi High Council.]]
A [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] [[Human/Legends|Human]], An'ya Kuro was [[Jedi training/Legends|trained]] in the ways of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]] by the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]], attaining the rank of [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]] and constructing a [[Color/Legends|purple]]-bladed [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]]. Showing much devotion to the Force and the [[Jedi Code/Legends|Jedi Code]], Kuro gone extreme on the teaching of attachments, shedding her own name and taking up the moniker the Dark Woman and said to be uncomfortable with connections with others<ref name="Jedi: Aayla Secura">''[[Jedi: Aayla Secura]]''</ref>. During her time as a Knight, Kuro began to travel [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] to find [[Force-sensitive/Legends|Force-sensitive]] children that the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Republic's]] screening process might have missed. In concert with the Order's [[Acquisition Division/Legends|Acquisition Division]], one of Kuro's early successes was the discovery of a young [[Ki-Adi-Mundi/Legends|Ki-Adi-Mundi]] on [[Cerea/Legends|Cerea]].<ref name="VOJ" />

While Kuro was negotiating with the child's father in the family farm, a gang of raiders came to steal the harvest of the household. Ki-Adi-Mundi was immediately hidden because of the special status of boys on Cerea&mdash;the birth rate for female Cereans to males was twenty-to-one, and raiders would steal young boys to raise as their own. At first, the Dark Woman wished to fight the gang, but the boy's father asked her not to intervene. Indeed, even if the raiders were defeated on the spot, they would probably come back for revenge after the departure of the Jedi. Knowing all of that, Kuro put her lightsaber back and witnessed the raid. Following this new violent experience, Ki-Adi-Mundi's father consented to let his son go. The Dark Woman was urged to take the child with her before the patriarch could change his mind.<ref name="VOJ" /> Returning to [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] with the [[Cerean/Legends|Cerean]] child, Kuro convinced the [[Jedi High Council/Legends|Jedi High Council]] to allow Ki-Adi-Mundi to begin training despite being older than most accepted [[Jedi Initiate/Legends|Jedi Initiates]]. When he was old enough, the High Council chose to assign Ki-Adi-Mundi to [[Jedi Master/Legends|Master]] [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]] for his Jedi training, lest an emotional relationship develop between Kuro and the young Cerean.<ref name="Outlander" />

Kuro utilized unconventionally harsh training methods which were nonetheless effective, and the High Council often assigned difficult trainees to her. These methods often produced strong Jedi that inherited a hint of Kuro's darkness, as visible in her former Padawan [[Jon Antilles]].<ref name="Blast Radius" /> However, the harsh training conditions she imposed on her students sometimes led to failure.<ref name="Outlander" /> At some point, Kuro discovered a Force-sensitive baby in the slums of [[Nar Shaddaa/Legends|Nar Shaddaa]]. Kuro brought the child to Coruscant to receive training. There, the child took the name [[Aurra Sing/Legends|Aurra Sing]]. Sing showed aggressive tendencies that led the Council to assign her to Kuro as a "problem case." Their efforts were in vain, however, and by age nine, Sing had still not attained the level of [[Padawan/Legends|Padawan]].<ref name="Aurra's Song" /> While at Kuro's training ground on [[Ord Namurt]]<ref name="POTJ">''[[Power of the Jedi Sourcebook]]''</ref> Sing was kidnapped by [[Pirate/Legends|space pirates]] who convinced the young Jedi that she was sold off by her master. Sing, who had never been close to Kuro, believed the lie. Thus began a lifelong grudge against the Jedi.<ref name="Aurra's Song" />

===Exile and return===
{{Quote|What a bizarre woman. I'd heard she was dead.|Mace Windu|<ref name="Star Wars (1998) 13">[[Star Wars (1998) 13|''Star Wars'' (1998) 13]]</ref>}}
[[File:DarkWomancomic.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The Dark Woman during the Clone Wars]]
Demoralized by the loss of Sing, Kuro retreated to [[Cophrigin V]] to meditate on her role as a Jedi, her training techniques, and the future.<ref name="CSWE" /> In [[32 BBY/Legends|32 BBY]], after twelve years of solitude, Kuro returned to Coruscant just as Ki-Adi-Mundi, now a famed [[Jedi Knight/Legends|Jedi Knight]], was preparing for a mission to [[Tatooine/Legends|Tatooine]]. Before his departure, Kuro warned her former Padawan to take considerable care on Tatooine, as she had foreseen a great darkness approaching in her dreams.<ref name="Outlander" />

Kuro later sparred with Ki-Adi-Mundi's new Padawan [[Darth Krayt|A'Sharad Hett]] in a training room at the Jedi Temple. Hett would not continue his training until he received a lesson from Kuro. The Dark Woman attacked Hett fiercely with her lightsaber and her own words, trying to enrage him. Hett stayed in control, phrasing passages from the Jedi Code and passed his test according to Kuro.<ref name="Star Wars (1998) 13" />

Two years thereafter, the [[Duel on Coruscant (30 BBY)|assassination]] of two Jedi verified the rumors of Sing's return as a Jedi-hunting assassin and bounty hunter. Kuro requested that the Jedi Council place her in charge of the [[Hunt for Aurra Sing|hunt]] for her former Padawan, but she was denied on the grounds of her connection to Sing. Instead, Ki-Adi-Mundi, A'Sharad Hett, and [[Adi Gallia/Legends|Adi Gallia]] were dispatched to track Sing and bring her to justice.<ref name="The Hunt for Aurra Sing" />

Kuro returned to Cophrigin V, unaware that Sing had been hired to assassinate her. The Jedi task force converged on Kuro's retreat just as Sing prepared to strike. Hett engaged Sing in battle and subdued the bounty hunter, but was forced to tap into his anger to ensure victory. Discouraged by the darkness he had seen in himself, Hett wished to give up on his Jedi training until Kuro offered to train him to control his anger. As the Jedi prepared to depart with Sing in tow, a meteor shower struck their landing site, forcing a hasty departure leaving the assassin behind.<ref name="The Hunt for Aurra Sing" />

===Clone Wars===
Kuro accompanied Master [[Mace Windu/Legends|Windu]] to [[Geonosis/Legends|Geonosis]] where she aided in the starfighter battle against Captain [[Cavik Toth]] under the command of [[Adi Gallia/Legends|Adi Gallia]].<ref name="Star Wars: Jedi Starfighter" /> During the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]], Kuro chose to aid the Republic as a [[Spy/Legends|spy]] rather than a general. Together with [[Tholme/Legends|Tholme]] and [[Aayla Secura/Legends|Aayla Secura]], Kuro infiltrated [[Devaron/Legends|Devaron]] to verify rumors of a [[Confederacy of Independent Systems/Legends|Separatist]] base.<ref name="Jedi: Aayla Secura" />

During their mission, Kuro was observed by Sing, who was on the planet to assassinate the [[Devaronian/Legends|Devaronian]] [[Senator/Legends|senator]]. Sing sprung a trap that pinned Tholme and Kuro under cavern rocks, but the young Secura was able to subdue Sing. The injured Jedi Masters recovered with bacta treatments and returned to Coruscant.<ref name="Jedi: Aayla Secura" />

===Great Jedi Purge===
{{Quote|Your power is at an ebb, Dark Woman.|Darth Vader|<ref name="Extinction" />}}
[[File:Anya-old.jpg|thumb|left|120px|Kuro confronts Darth Vader.]]
With the onset of the [[Great Jedi Purge/Legends|Great Jedi Purge]] and the establishment of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]], Kuro sought safety on [[Cophrigin V]], where she built a great garden and lived as a hermit. When Kuro's hiding place was discovered by [[Mara Jade Skywalker|Mara Jade]], an [[Emperor's Hand/Legends|Emperor's Hand]] and one of Palpatine's personal assassins, [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] arrived to [[Duel on Cophrigin V|personally kill]] the unorthodox Jedi Master. After a brief discussion concerning extinction and evolution, Kuro told Vader that she already accepted her fate, but nonetheless put up a fight.<ref name="Extinction" />

Eventually during their duel, Vader brought down a huge tree on top of Kuro, trapping her. With a slash of his lightsaber, he ended her life. She merged with the Force and told him he still had the power left in him to become Anakin Skywalker again. Enraged, Vader tried to strike her [[Force ghost/Legends|Force ghost]] with his blade, but Kuro's presence simply disappeared into the light of the Force.<ref name="Extinction" />

==Personality and traits==
{{Quote|We ''all'' have a darkness within us, A'Sharad Hett. It is what makes us living beings, bound by the Force. We can never brush that darkness away. It is within us always. We can only learn to control it, like a dangerous beast that must be kept upon a chain. I know of this darkness. I have seen those who become ''lost'' to it, like that creature down there.|An'ya Kuro to A'Sharad Hett|<ref name="Star Wars (1998) 31">[[Star Wars (1998) 31|''Star Wars'' (1998) 31]]</ref>}}
[[File:DarkWomanAsharadHett-SWREP13.jpg|thumb|right|220px|An'ya Kuro was a grueling Jedi Master.]]
An'ya Kuro was an unorthodox and mysterious Jedi Master. She believed strongly in the Jedi philosophy of humility, so strongly that she abandoned her own name and adopted the name Dark Woman. Kuro was well known for training difficult or troubled Padawans such as Aurra Sing and A'Sharad Hett. However, her teaching methods were brutal and, to some, disturbing. Her teaching methods most likely contributed to Aurra Sing's hatred of the Jedi Master.

Though Kuro displayed some dark traits, such as her brutal training methods, she was still able to become a Force ghost after her death, indicating that, underneath her mysterious, unorthodox and at times brutal exterior, she was devoted to the light side of the Force. Kuro also believed that Darth Vader still had enough good in him to turn away from the dark side and her Force ghost even referred to him as Anakin, the name of the man he had once been.

==Powers and abilities==
{{Quote|There's no need for concern, Master Windu. I warned you; her testing methods are notoriously&hellip;unorthodox!''"<br />"''Unorthodox? The ways of her teaching are brutal&hellip;and disturbing!|Ki-Adi Mundi and Even Piell|<ref name="Star Wars (1998) 13" />}}
[[File:DarkWomanTCG.jpg|thumb|left|200px|An'ya Kuro wielding her purple-bladed lightsaber]]
An'ya Kuro was a very powerful Jedi and was known to possess many Force powers uncommon among the Jedi, such as the ability to [[Plant Surge|control plant matter]],<ref name="Extinction" /> and [[Force cloak|bend light around her]] to render herself invisible. She even appeared to be able to [[Phase|pass through solid objects]].<ref name="Emissaries to Malastare">>''[[Star Wars: Emissaries to Malastare]]''</ref><ref name="CWCG">''[[The Clone Wars Campaign Guide]]''</ref> She also possessed the ability to use the Force to [[Teleportation (Force power)/Legends|teleport]].<ref name="Emissaries to Malastare" /> During the hunt for Aurra Sing, Kuro had additionally shown to possess an incredible talent for [[Force healing/Legends|Force healing]], being able to casually heal a misfired blaster wound almost instantly. After her death, Kuro appeared before Darth Vader as a Force ghost.

Her lightsaber was particularly ornate, with an organic style to it, modified or perhaps built with artificial plant vines wrapping around it.<ref name="Extinction" /> Though emitting a purple blade throughout most of her career as a Jedi, Kuro briefly wielded a blue-bladed weapon during the Clone Wars before returning to [[An'ya Kuro's lightsaber|her original lightsaber]] after the war. She proved capable of holding her own against [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] in a lightsaber duel, despite her advanced age. She utilized several acrobatic maneuvers during the duel, which suggested she was possibly a practitioner of [[Form IV/Legends|Ataru]]. Like Grand Master Yoda, her old age did not seem to limit her speed and dexterity, and at one point she even disarmed the Sith Lord, something very few other Jedi had been able to do. However, she had to ambush him to accomplish this. Kuro was also proficient in the use of [[Jar'Kai/Legends|Jar'Kai]].

==Behind the scenes==
The Dark Woman was created by [[Jan Strnad]] as an incidental character for "[[Vow of Justice]]".<ref name="cswu">{{WebCite|url=http://www.cswu.cz/woc/int/jan_strnad_en.html|text=Interview with Jan S. Strnad|archivedate=20010217004748}}</ref>

The Dark Woman also appears as an action figure in a set including [[Darth Krayt|A'Sharad Hett]] and a comic book depicting the hunt for [[Aurra Sing/Legends|Aurra Sing]]. The comic ''[[Jedi: Aayla Secura]]'' depicts her lightsaber with a blue blade instead of her typical purple.

